y, novels, art, and religion, the literary scholars in this collection offer new and intriguing readings of these canonical authors. Informed by contemporary currents such as new materialism, cognitive studies, media theory, and post-secularism, their essays demonstrate the volatility of the core ideas opened up by materialism and the possibilities of an aesthetic vitalism of form.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aAesthetics in literature. 0aEnglish literaturexHistory and criticismy18th century. 0aEnglish literaturey18th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aFrench literaturexHistory and criticismy18th century. 0aFrench literaturey18th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aMaterialism in literature. 0aPhilosophy in literature. 0aVitalism in literature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / French.2bisacsh1 aAlvarez, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aConway, Alison, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aEllenzweig, Sarah, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKramnick, Jonathan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLandreth, Sara, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMack, Ruth, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcMurran, Mary Helen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcMurran, Mary Helen, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aSoni, Vivasvan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aStalnaker, Joanna, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTunstall, Kate E., econtributor.4ctb4http